{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 06:25:04.490121", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Network-wide Layer 3 reachability is healthy and OSPF routing is consistent across core, distribution, and server-access routers.\n- A single, clear anomaly is present: consistent ~1 second latency on all traffic sourced from or destined to the DNS server (10.200.0.2). This introduces ~1s DNS lookup delay for clients.\n- Root cause is localized to dns_server eth0: a traffic control netem delay of 1 second is configured on its egress.\n\nDetection and key observations\n- End-to-end reachability:\n  - Broad ping matrix shows near-zero loss and low RTTs (typically 2–5 ms) between access subnets and server farm, except flows involving DNS.\n  - Example normal RTTs:\n    - host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_0: 1.9–4.7 ms\n    - host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer: 2.0–3.1 ms\n- DNS path latencies (abnormal):\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server: RTT ≈ 1002–1003 ms (4/4 received)\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server: RTT ≈ 1003 ms (4/4 received)\n  - dns_server -> access hosts: average RTTs 1.4–1.5 s with spikes to ~2 s in reachability set\n- User-experienced impact validated:\n  - HTTP to web99.local from host_1_1_1_1 shows curl timing:\n    - DNS namelookup ~1.00–1.03 s\n    - Connect completes ~1.03 s from start (i.e., ~30 ms after DNS), total ~2.07–2.14 s\n  - This isolates the bulk of added delay to DNS resolution.\n- DNS server service state:\n  - dns_server is listening on 10.200.0.2:53 and 127.0.0.1:53 (netstat shows multiple LISTENs; service is up).\n- Network control plane:\n  - OSPF routes present and sane on server_access_router and all core/dist routers. Server VLAN 10.200.0.0/24 is connected on server_access_router and learned appropriately elsewhere.\n  - Access hosts have valid DHCP-leased addresses and default gateways:\n    - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.22/24 via 10.1.1.1\n    - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.25/24 via 10.2.1.1\n- Critical evidence on the DNS server:\n  - tc/qdisc on dns_server eth0:\n    - qdisc netem root delay 1s (functions.get_tc_statistics: “delay 1s”)\n  - dns_server ifconfig/ip addr explicitly shows eth0 is under qdisc netem.\n\nFault localization\n- Faulty device: dns_server\n- Faulty interface: eth0\n- Fault domain: host egress queuing on the DNS server itself (not in the routed path).\n- Network forwarding/routing elements (FRR routers, switching) do not exhibit anomalies; RTTs and routes are otherwise normal.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- A Linux traffic control netem delay of 1 second is configured on dns_server’s eth0. Because ICMP replies and DNS responses egress via eth0, the qdisc injects ~1 second artificial delay into:\n  - All ping replies from dns_server (making RTT ~1 s as observed from clients).\n  - All DNS query responses to clients (explaining curl namelookup ~1 s).\n- No packet loss accompanies the delay; this is consistent with a netem delay-only profile (no loss configured).\n\nScope and impact\n- Affects all clients resolving names via dns_server (10.200.0.2), adding ~1 second to each DNS lookup.\n- Web access via web99.local works but is slowed by ~1 second due to DNS; subsequent TCP connection and data transfer are normal.\n- Other services from dns_server would also incur the added 1 s in their outbound traffic path.\n\nNon-issues confirmed\n- OSPF topology/routing tables across router_core_1/2/3, router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1, and server_access_router are healthy.\n- Connectivity to server farm components (web servers, load balancer) is normal with low RTTs and no loss.\n- DHCP appears to be functioning; hosts have valid leases and routes.\n- No evidence of congestion, loops, or asymmetric routing elsewhere in the network.\n\nConclusion\n- Anomaly detected: yes — systemic ~1 s latency on DNS traffic.\n- Fault localization: dns_server eth0 egress.\n- Root cause: tc netem delay 1s configured on dns_server eth0, introducing an artificial 1 s delay on responses.", "generation_info": 